    {
        "content": "<p>Only closed intervals in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> are compact, so it's no wonder that you failed to close the goal - there simply is no proof with which the sorry could be filled it. Are you sure compactness is actually what you want, and not something like boundedness?</p>",
        "id": 491839141,
        "sender_full_name": "Ben Eltschig",
        "timestamp": 1735959129
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also, you can remove the <code>variable [TopologicalSpace ℝ] [OrderTopology ℝ]</code> line. <code>ℝ</code> already comes with those instances as soon as you <code>ìmport Mathlib</code>, introducing them again is only going to cause trouble.</p>",
        "id": 491839320,
        "sender_full_name": "Ben Eltschig",
        "timestamp": 1735959336
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"646363\">Ben Eltschig</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Proving.20compactness.20of.20.280.2Cr.5D.20from.20.5B0.2Cr.5D/near/491839141\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Only closed intervals in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> are compact, so it's no wonder that you failed to close the goal - there simply is no proof with which the sorry could be filled it. Are you sure compactness is actually what you want, and not something like boundedness?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Boundedness could possibly be the right direction given the domain of the set. I'd appreciate any help.</p>",
